{"text": "2 \u0307\u03b72 = \u0307\u03c4 y = 4rxy\u03c4 x \u22122\u2206\u03c4 z\n\n= 4rxy\n\n\u221a\n\n2\u03b11 \u22122\u2206(2i\u03b11\u03b72).\n\n(40)\n\nFrom general grounds, the parity operator 2i\u03b11\u03b72 is\n\nreal. Therefore, suppose we multiply the left-hand side\n\nof the first line in Eqs. (40) by i\u03b72 and the second line\n\nby i\u03b11 these two equations become equivalent to\n\ni\u03b72 \u0307\u03b11 = i4rxy\u03b72\n\n2\n\n(41)\n\ni\u03b11 \u0307\u03b72 = \u22122\n\n\u221a\n\n2\u2206\u03b12\n\n1\u03b72 \u22124irxy\u03b12\n\n1.\n\nThis leads to\n\ni d\n\ndt(\u03b11\u03b72) = 4irxy(\u03b72\n\n2 \u2212\u03b12\n\n1) \u22122\n\n\u221a\n\n2\u2206\u03b12\n\n1\u03b72.\n\n(42)\n\nMajorana fermions satisfy that \u03b72\n\n2 = \u03b12\n\n1 = 1\n\n2. Therefore,\n\nfrom the differentials, this equation becomes\n\ni d\n\ndt(\u03b11\u03b72) = \u2212\u2206\n\n\u221a\n\n2\u03b72.\n\n(43)\n\n(i) Eq. (43) agrees with the Heisenberg equation of\n\nmotion \u0307\u03c4 z = 2\u2206\u03c4 y. In general, this equation leads to a\n\nunitary evolution in time. Suppose that \u03b11(t) and \u03b72(t)\n\nwould acquire a decoherence such that \u03b11(t) \u2192\u03b11.e\u2212t/\u03c41\n\nand \u03b72(t) \u2192\u03b72.e\u2212t/\u03c42, then on the left-hand side we\n\nwould have a function in e\u2212t\n\n\u03c41 \u2212t\n\n\u03c42 whereas on the right-\n\nhand side we have a function in e\u2212t/\u03c42. It is also interest-\n\ning to comment that the \u03c3z variable related to the usual\n\nspin-boson model satisfies a similar equation as for the\n\n\u03c4 z spin\n\n\u0307\u03c3z = 2\u2206\u03c3y.\n\n(44)\n\nThe correspondence between the spin-boson models with\n\nthe \u03c3 spin (of one sphere) and with the \u03c4 spin can be\n\nunderstood as \u03c3z \u2192\u03c4 x (corresponding to the variable\n\ncoupling to the bath), \u03c3y \u2192\u03c4 y and \u03c3x \u2192\u2212\u03c4 z. In terms\n\nof the Majorana fermions \u03b11 and \u03b72, Eq. (44) would im-\n\nply \u0307\u03b11 = \u22122\u2206\u03b72 such that we verify that a solution with\n\nan exponential decoherence would now be possible. We\n\nalso verify the occurrence of decoherence when evaluat-\n\ning \u0308\u03c3z to second-order in \u03bbk. Therefore, all these results\n\nagree with the fact that the Majorana fermions \u03b11 and \u03b72\n\ncan admit a coherent unitary dynamics when the bath is\n\nlinearly coupled to the \u03c4-spin along x direction. Below,\n\nwe verify the coherent dynamics in the x \u2212y plane for\n\nthe \u03c4-spin.", "embedding": [0.038779177, -0.006702594, 0.031251006, 0.00959583, -0.00148781, -0.020105952, -0.00080142164, -0.022856323, -0.064873554, 0.086414404, 0.03460048, -0.0064456286, 0.011390648, -0.027705874, -0.015840422, 0.013033585, -0.007230609, -0.036794625, -0.08463844, 0.04108528, 0.023506213, 0.0059417966, -0.05112292, -0.0024970183, -0.01596764, 0.030233752, 0.010911437, 0.029695988, 0.04497559, 0.04335194, 0.046086915, -0.011067895, 0.009830994, -0.023114216, 0.01641298, 0.024886763, 0.011071851, -0.0149742225, 0.05914483, -0.026160132, 0.04840367, 0.022441342, 0.018609768, -0.010375508, -0.051902942, 0.012110692, -0.047588084, 0.0015371465, -0.035630308, -0.064433426, 0.028560998, -0.019559365, 0.039529793, -0.0050015086, 0.0066229817, -0.034372967, 0.008830342, 0.022226868, -0.026870826, -0.017116332, 0.019216128, -0.013526374, 0.039939307, -0.07010314, 0.014894904, 0.048689, -0.0055634673, 0.049609322, -0.028758133, -0.043387484, -0.022033168, -0.023468606, -0.037211142, 0.016956069, -0.05249055, 0.044463016, 0.02621737, -0.03258412, -0.06370419, -0.02714367, 0.0026338801, -0.01971804, -0.021833502, 0.016861746, 0.0125511605, -0.023963347, 0.009950736, -0.027941527, -0.01462711, -0.0012858792, 0.002306117, 0.03707158, -0.033469938, 0.015624411, 0.04607282, 0.040899977, 0.008703922, 0.03790816, 0.018580822, -0.0032219717, 0.005656089, 0.04412308, -0.025762927, 0.06752006, -0.039986912, 0.048024546, 0.0032139574, 0.041601866, -0.0026662666